[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    100[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;235;203;139mThe problem:[38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;192;197;206m EventBridge invokes Lambda asynchronously by default. Asynchronous Lambda invocations retry twice on failure (3 total attempts) before sending to a DLQ (if configured). Without a DLQ configured, failed invocations are silently dropped after retries.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    101[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    102[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;192;197;206mAdditionally, if the Lambda succeeds on retry but the first attempt also partially succeeded (e.g., wrote a partial record to DynamoDB before timing out), you get duplicate or inconsistent state. The recipe has no idempotency mechanism (no conditional writes, no deduplication on message_id).[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    103[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    104[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;235;203;139mSuggested fix:[38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;192;197;206m Add to the prerequisites or architecture section: "Configure a dead-letter queue (SQS) on the Lambda's asynchronous invocation configuration. Use a DynamoDB conditional write ([38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140mConditionExpression: attribute_not_exists(message_id)[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;192;197;206m) in Step 5 to make draft storage idempotent. This prevents duplicate drafts if EventBridge retries the Lambda after a transient failure."[K
